<HEADLINE>
Chronology of North Korean nuclear crisis
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
BEIJING, Sept 11
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Key dates in the crisis over North 
Korea's nuclear weapons drive:
</P>
<P>
1994
</P>
<P>
North Korea and the United States sign a nuclear safeguard 
accord after Pyongyang vows to freeze and eventually dismantle its 
nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
2002
</P>
<P>
Oct: North Korea reportedly admits to US special envoy James 
Kelly that it is running a uranium enrichment program in violation 
of the 1994 nuclear safeguard accord.
</P>
<P>
Nov 14: The United States suspends fuel oil shipments to North 
Korea promised under the 1994 accord.
</P>
<P>
Dec 12: North Korea says it is reactivating nuclear facilities 
frozen under the accord because of power shortages.
</P>
<P>
Dec 21-25: North Korea removes seals and monitoring cameras from 
its main nuclear complex at Yongbyon, north of Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Dec 27: UN's International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
inspectors expelled from Yongbyon.
</P>
<P>
2003
</P>
<P>
Jan 10: Pyongyang withdraws from the nuclear Non-Proliferation 
Treaty (NPT).
</P>
<P>
Feb 12: The IAEA declares North Korea in violation of 
non-proliferation accords and refers the crisis to the UN Security 
Council.
</P>
<P>
Feb 26: North Korea restarts its five-megawatt nuclear reactor 
at Yongbyon facilities, US officials say.
</P>
<P>
April 18: North Korea says it has begun reprocessing more than 
8,000 spent nuclear fuel rods to make weapons-grade plutonium.
</P>
<P>
April 23: The United States, North Korea and China meet for 
three days of talks in Beijing. North Korea admits to possessing 
nuclear weapons, according to the US side. Pyongyang submits a "bold 
proposal" for resolving the crisis.
</P>
<P>
July 16: The White House says North Korea has informed the 
United States of completing the reprocessing of the 8,000 spent fuel 
rods on June 30. 
</P>
<P>
Aug 13: North Korea asks for a non-aggression pact with the 
United States to resolve the nuclear stand-off.
</P>
<P>
Aug 27-29: Six-nation nuclear talks start in Beijing. North 
Korea threatens to conduct a nuclear test and declare itself a 
nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
Oct 2: North Korea says it has produced enough weapons-grade 
plutonium for half-a-dozen atomic bombs as a step towards boosting 
its nuclear deterrent. 
</P>
<P>
Nov 21: The Korean Peninsula Energy Development Organization 
(KEDO), an international consortium set up to build safe nuclear 
power reactors for North Korea, suspends the 4.6 billion dollar 
project for one year.
</P>
<P>
2004
</P>
<P>
Jan 1: North Korea reaffirms in a New Year message that it is 
ready to resolve the nuclear crisis peacefully while vowing to take 
the "toughest" measures against any US "hardline" stance toward 
Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Jan 6: North Korea offers to refrain from testing and producing 
nuclear weapons in a "bold concession". US Secretary of State Colin 
Powell says he is encouraged by the offer.
</P>
<P>
Jan 22: IAEA chief Mohamed ElBaradei says North Korea's nuclear 
program is the world's most dangerous non-proliferation issue.
</P>
<P>
Feb 4: Abdul Qadeer Khan, the founder of Pakistan's atomic 
program, admits proliferating nuclear technology after two-month 
investigation into the leaking of nuclear secrets to Iran, Libya and 
North Korea.
</P>
<P>
Feb 24: Second round of six-party talks are held in Beijing but 
end without concrete progress. China says "severe" differences 
remain.
</P>
<P>
May 22: Japanese Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi visits Kim 
Jong-il in Pyongyang and the North Korean leader says he wants a 
solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
June 23-25: Third round of six-way talks held in Beijing. No 
progress reported but parties agree to meet again for a fourth round 
in September.
</P>
<P>
Aug 23: North Korea says it is "impossible" to attend more talks 
because of "hostile" US policy, labeling Bush an "imbecile" and a 
"tyrant" who is worse than Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
Sept 28: The United States warns North Korea it might be 
reported to the UN Security Council if it refuses participation in 
six-party talks.
</P>
<P>
2005
</P>
<P>
Feb 10: North Korea indefinitely suspends participation in talks 
and says it has manufactured nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
March 16: North Korea lashes out at US Secretary of State 
Condoleezza Rice for calling the communist state an "outpost of 
tyranny" and rules out new talks.
</P>
<P>
May 5: The International Atomic Energy Agency estimates that 
North Korea has close to six nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
May 13: US and North Korean officials meet in New York.
</P>
<P>
June 8: North Korea says it has a stockpile of nuclear bombs and 
is building more such weapons. It also says no nuclear talks unless 
Washington meets unspecified conditions.
</P>
<P>
June 17: North Korean leader Kim Jong-Il tells the South Korean 
unification minister his country is willing to resume stalled 
six-nation talks on its nuclear programme in July.
</P>
<P>
June 23: North Korea says it would scrap its nuclear weapons 
only if the United States removed the nuclear threat to the Korean 
peninsula as a first step.
</P>
<P>
July 5: North Korea restates its rejection of a US demand that 
it disarm its nuclear weapons before the new round of six-nation 
talks could begin, warning   there would be no progress if the US 
did not change its "high-handed" stance.
</P>
<P>
July 9: North Korea's official media say the country agrees to 
return to six-way talks in the last week of July.
</P>
<P>
July 12: South Korea offers to route some 2,000 megawatts of 
electricity to North Korea and to provide 500,000 tonnes of rice if 
Pyongyang gives up its nuclear drive. It also offers to provide 
funds and raw materials to help the North produce daily necessities 
such as garments, footwear and soap from 2006.
</P>
<P>
July 25: The US and North Korea hold a rare bilateral meeting in 
Beijing, the first of at least nine in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
July 26: Fourth round of six-party talks begins.
</P>
<P>
Aug 4: North Korea insists it has the right to operate nuclear 
programs for peaceful purposes, which emerges as the main sticking 
point in negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
Aug 7: Six-party talks enter a three-week recess after 
participating nations fail to reach agreement on what should be in a 
joint document outlining how North Korea will dump its nuclear 
arsenal and what it would get in return.
</P>
<P>
Aug 29: North Korea says it will not return to the talks as 
scheduled, blaming the delay on military drills between the United 
States and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Sept 8: China announces that the six-party talks will resume on 
September 13.
</P>
